CONTENTS

This version of Microemacs is a Linux port of the original Microemacs 3.12
release by Daniel Lawrence. A few additions have been made in order to

1) correct some minor bugs and compilation problems
2) provide better support for the arrow keys
3) allow window change of sizes to take effect on size of text displayed
4) introduce more complete and more reliable justification routines
   (new key bindings Esc-I Esc-J Esc-Q Esc-T)

Microemacs is a small but nevertheless very powerful emacs clone. 
It can be almost entirely customized through the user configuration 
file ~/.emacsrc

Included with the distribution is a system wide initialization file  
emacs.rc  allowing efficient handling of TeX and LaTeX files


COMPILATION AND INSTALLATION

* To compile microemacs-5.03, just type "make"

* Installation: type "make install"

* Compilation --and-- installation: type "make all"

* After installing, cleaning of object files is obtained by "make clean"


PORTING NOTES (macOS)

The tree builds on macOS (Apple Clang, arm64 and x86_64) as well as Linux.
A few things to be aware of if porting to another Unix-like system:

* The Makefile uses "CC ?= cc" so it picks up Apple Clang on macOS and gcc
  on Linux without modification. CFLAGS includes "-g"; remove it for a
  release build. The tree carries its own termcap/tparam implementation
  (termcap.c, tparam.c), so no -ltermcap / -lcurses link is needed.

* window.c uses <termios.h> and <sys/ioctl.h> for struct winsize and
  TIOCGWINSZ. Older revisions of this tree included <asm/termios.h> and
  <asm/ioctls.h>, which are Linux-kernel-private and not portable.

* scopen() in unix.c queries the terminal size with TIOCGWINSZ on fd 0,
  1, then 2, falling back to termcap (li/co), then to the LINES/COLUMNS
  environment variables, then to a 24x80 default. This makes the editor
  usable when stdin is not a tty (e.g. when launched under lldb).

* The signal handler check_resize() (window.c) returns void, as POSIX
  requires. It bails out early if curwp is NULL, since SIGWINCH can
  arrive before edinit() has set up the first window.

* macOS libc's __strcpy_chk traps (SIGTRAP, "Trace trap") when the
  source and destination of strcpy() overlap. getval() in eval.c
  legitimately returns a pointer that aliases its argument (e.g. it
  returns token+1 to strip a leading quote). Callers that needed to
  copy that result back into the input buffer were converted to use
  memmove() in exec.c and eval.c. If you add new code that does
  strcpy(buf, getval(buf)) or similar, use memmove() instead.

* eproto.h previously declared "void crypt(char *, unsigned)", which
  collides with libc's crypt(3) on macOS (and any system whose
  <unistd.h> declares it). The declaration was unused and has been
  removed.

* Several C source files acquired explicit #include lines for headers
  that older glibc pulled in transitively but macOS / modern Clang do
  not: <ctype.h> in basic.c and word.c, <unistd.h> in file.c, termcap.c
  and tparam.c, <fcntl.h> in termcap.c, and <stdlib.h>/<string.h>
  unconditionally in termcap.c and tparam.c.

* nullproc(), unarg(), dcline(), edinit() and main() were given
  explicit return statements; modern Clang treats falling off the end
  of a non-void function as an error by default.


